At 08:11 CAT, the Rand traded at 17.0725 against the United States Dollar, 0.1% weaker than its previous close. In global markets, the dollar was up about 0.2% against a basket of currencies. Consumer inflation likely eased to 7.2% year-on-year in December from 7.4% in November, according to analysts polled by Reuters. The report from Statistics South Africa is due at around 10:00 CAT. Meanwhile, retail sales (ZARET=ECI) are expected to have fallen 0.2% year-on-year in November, compared with a 0.6% drop in October. That report is due to be published at 1300 CAT. The Rand fell steeply on Monday on mounting concerns over crippling power cuts, which prompted President Cyril Ramaphosa to cancel plans to visit the World Economic Forum in Davos. The currency closed with little changed on Tuesday. The government's benchmark 2030 bond was slightly stronger in early deals on Wednesday, with the yield down 4 basis points at 9.820%. --Reuters--